SE News
HD Danish bank boycotts Israels Hapoalim, Swedish bank asks for clarifications. Bennett thanks NY lawmaker for bill that would bar funding for schools blacklisting Israel
BY HERB KEINON and LAHAV HARKOV; JTA contributed to this report
WC 699 words
PD 2 February 2014
SN The Jerusalem Post
SC JPST
ED Daily
PG 01
LA English
CY Copyright, 2014, The Jerusalem Post, All Rights Reserved. Distributed by NewsBank, inc.

LP 

A canceled meeting of key cabinet ministers called last week to discuss the creeping boycott of Israeli companies and banks has not been rescheduled, even as two major European banks recently decided on actions against their Israeli counterparts.

Swedens Nordea Bank and Denmarks Danske Bank have both taken steps against Israeli banks involved in construction in the settlements, Walla reported on Saturday.

TD 

Danske bank, the largest in Denmark, recently said on its website that it was boycotting Bank Hapoalim for legal and ethical reasons. And Nordea Bank, the largest in Scandinavia, has asked for clarifications from Bank Leumi and Mizrahi-Tefahot Bank regarding their activities beyond the Green Line.

The ministerial meeting to discuss the boycotts was canceled last week, because of tension between Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Economy Minister Naftali Bennett. The two men are scheduled to meet at Sundays weekly cabinet meetings for the first time since Bennetts sharp criticism last week of Netanyahu for entertaining the idea that settlements might come under Palestinian rule in a future agreement. Threatened with being fired from the cabinet, Bennett issued an apology of sorts to defuse a coalition crisis.

Over the weekend, Bennett citing a New York State legislative initiative said that it was possible to boycott the boycotters. His remark came in a conversation with New York State Sen. Jeffrey Klein, who sponsored a bill that would suspend funding to educational institutions that fund groups that boycott Israel.

The legislation passed the chamber by a 56-4 vote, and would ban state funding to colleges that fund organizations boycotting countries that host higher education institutions chartered by the Board of Regents of the University of the State of New York.

The bill was in response to the American Studies Associations recent boycott of Israeli universities.Bennett told Klein, who represents parts of Bronx and Westchester counties, that this legislation was an expression of moral clarity and moral courage at a time when most of the world is silent in the face of actions taken against Israel.

A similar bill introduced in the State Assembly last month by Speaker Sheldon Silver has 48 sponsors among the chambers 150 members. If it passes there, it will go to Gov. Andrew Cuomo for his signature before becoming a New York State law.

Meanwhile, State Department deputy spokeswoman Marie Harf related to the boycott movement at the departments daily press briefing on Friday, saying that the US thinks the boycotts are unhelpful of Israel, and we oppose them because we believe that in order to resolve these issues, we need to discuss them directly between the two parties at the negotiating table, and that that kind of action isnt helpful.

In Israel, MK Hilik Bar (Labor) said the boycotts will not help end the conflict, push forward peace talks or aid the Israeli or Palestinian economies. They happen because of settlement construction, but also because there is no optimism for the conflict to be solved and the existence of two, neighboring independent countries.

MK Nachman Shai (Labor) warned that Israel was facing an economic tsunami and that boycotts have passed the point of no return.

Together with other sanctions, the international community is starting a joint battle to pressure Israel, Shai said. Our nightmare is coming true and the government refuses to understand that things will never be the same.

Meretz chairwoman Zehava Gal-On called on Netanyahu to stop burying his head in the sand and immediately announce a total freeze of construction in settlements.

Continuing the occupation and settlements are not acceptable anymore, not just to European countries but to banks and private companies, Gal-On said. Their decisions can turn Israel into an outcast country, isolated like Cuba and South Africa.

The prime minister needs to wake up, because the world is losing patience and the threat of boycotts on Israel grows from day to day, she said.

HD EARNINGS POLL-Danske Bank Q4 pretax profit seen up 30 pct
WC 926 words
PD 3 February 2014
ET 05:49
SN Reuters News
SC LBA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Reuters Limited

LP 

TD 

* Danske Bank fourth quarter results
    * Due Thursday, Feb 6, at around 0700 GMT
    * Pretax profit seen rising to 2.92 bln DKK ($527.73 mln)

    COPENHAGEN, Feb 3 (Reuters) - Denmark's biggest financial institution Danske Bank
 is expected to report a 29.5 percent rise in fourth quarter pretax profit, aided by
declining loan impairments, a Reuters poll of analysts showed on Monday.
    (Figures are in millions of Danish crowns, except EPS and dividend which are in crowns).

HD Danske Bank pays first dividend for five years
WC 352 words
PD 6 February 2014
ET 05:47
SN Agence France Presse
SC AFPR
LA English
CY Copyright Agence France-Presse, 2014 All reproduction and presentation rights reserved.

LP 

Denmark's biggest bank, Danske Bank, is to pay its first dividend for five years, it said on Thursday reporting a higher annual profit amid an improving Danish economy.

The intended two-kroner (0.27 euros, $0.36) dividend represents 28 percent of net profit for the year, cheering investors but lagging behind some Swedish rivals which pay out more than half of their profits in dividends.

TD 

"We aim to pay dividends of about 40 percent of net profit as soon as it is prudent," Danske Bank said.

Annual net profit jumped 51 percent to 7.115 billion kroner (953 million euros, $1.29 billion), helped by cost reductions.

At the beginning of the year the bank said the number would be between 7.5 billion and 10 billion kroner, a target it later had to revise downwards twice.

Total income fell 12 percent to 40 billion kroner, dragged down by a 2.0-percent fall in net interest income, 45 percent in net trading income and 50 percent in net insurance income.

"We expect a slight pickup in growth in 2014," the bank said.

Fourth-quarter net profit rose 25 percent to 1.923 billion kroner, which was lower than the 2.17 billion predicted by analysts polled by Dow Jones Newswires.

In September, Danske Bank ousted chief executive Eivind Kolding after just 19 months, saying the job required someone with more banking experience.

A controversial advertising campaign launched under Kolding was widely seen as alienating thousands of customers, and his successor Thomas Borgen has admitted that the bank was too quick to close some branches.

Borgen and chairman Ole Andersen said in a joint statement that 2013 was "a year of change and progress" for the bank, which is still feeling the effects of a financial crisis that sent Danish house prices tumbling.

"Our guidance for 2014 is based on expectations of slow and still fragile macroeconomic growth and a continuation of low interest rate levels in our core markets," the bank said.

HD "Danske Bank" earns EUR 2.94 million in net profit in Latvia in 2013
BY Airisa damsone
WC 131 words
PD 6 February 2014
ET 05:58
SN Latvian News Agency
SC LETA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 LETA .

LP 

RIGA, Feb 6 (NOZARE.LV) - "Danske Bank" earned EUR 2.94 million in net profit in Latvia in 2013, "Nozare.lv" learned from the bank.

"Danske Bank" income from basic operations totaled EUR 7.4 million. The cost/income ratio was 75 percent.

TD 

The bank's deposit portfolio grew 26 percent and reached EUR 218.7 million at the end of 2013.

"Danske Bank" loan portfolio grew 19 percent and amounted to EUR 302.5 million.

The amount of loans to corporate clients increased 73 percent to EUR 157.8 million.

"Danske Bank" is the Latvian branch of "Danske Bank Group", the largest bank in Denmark. "Danske Bank Group" is represented in 15 countries.

HD Danske Bank restores dividend as it seeks to reassure investors
BY By Richard Milne, Nordic Correspondent
WC 331 words
PD 6 February 2014
ET 02:58
SN Financial Times (FT.Com)
SC FTCMA
LA English
CY Copyright 2014 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.

LP 

Danske Bank has restored its dividend for the first time since 2007 as Denmark's biggest lender seeks to reassure investors the worst is behind it.

Danske is proposing a dividend of DKr2 per share for 2013, equivalent to 28 per cent of net profit.

TD 

That is modest by Scandinavian standards with the four big Swedish banks all paying out more than half of profits, with Swedbank leading the way with a pay-out ratio of 75 per cent.

But it reflects the difficulties that Danske, and Denmark, have suffered since the financial crisis as customers deserted the lender and it ejected its chief executive last year, complaining they wanted somebody "with stronger qualifications in banking".

Thomas Borgen, the new chief executive, said on Thursday as he unveiled fourth-quarter results: "The year 2013 was a time of progress for Danske Bank. We took steps to strengthen our position in the market, accelerated the execution of our strategy and contained costs. Our financial results improved, but they were still unsatisfactory."

One of Mr Borgen's first acts was to cut the previous target of achieving a 12 per cent return on equity by 2015 to 9 per cent. In 2013 it delivered 5 per cent. By contrast, Sweden's SEB reported a return on equity of 13 per cent in 2013.

Danske's net profit rose by 51 per cent last year to DKr7.1bn while costs fell by 1 per cent to DKr24bn. Mr Borgen announced a DKr1bn cost-cutting programme in October that would involve job losses.

The lender said it expected a net profit of DKr9bn-12bn this year and recommitted itself to reaching a 9 per cent return on equity next year.

"We still have a way to go to realise the full potential of Danske Bank, but we are confident that we are moving in the right direction," said Mr Borgen.

HD Danske Bank Proposes Dividend Payout; Danish Lender May Pay First Dividend in Five Years After Earnings Rise in Fourth Quarter
BY Gustav Sandstrom
WC 302 words
PD 5 February 2014
ET 21:44
SN The Wall Street Journal Online
SC WSJO
ED WSJ.com
LA English
CY Copyright 2014 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved.

LP 

Danish lender Danske Bank A/S Thursday reported rising fourth-quarter earnings, as narrowing loan losses helped compensate for a slight drop in net interest income, and proposed paying a dividend for the first time in several years.

Denmark's biggest bank by market capitalization reported net profit of 1.92 billion Danish kroner ($348 million) for the three months to Dec. 31, up from 1.15 billion kroner a year earlier but below analysts' expectations for 2.17 billion kroner.

TD 

"The Danish economy picked up throughout 2013," Danske Bank said. "Housing prices started to increase, but the turnaround is weak and the housing market remains a risk factor."

The bank, which hasn't paid a dividend for five years, said its board is proposing a dividend of 2 kroner per share for 2013, corresponding to 28% of the year's profits.

Danske Bank is winding down operations in Ireland, where it has taken losses in recent years in the wake of the crisis there, and it has also seen a less favorable economy in its Danish home market compared with rivals in Sweden and Norway. Its Chief Executive Thomas Borgen last autumn announced plans to reduce costs and boost efficiency.

The bank expects net profit of 9 billion-12 billion kroner in 2014 and remains committed to its target for return on equity over 9% in 2015 and over 12% in the longer term, it said.

Fourth-quarter net interest income fell to 5.68 billion kroner from 5.71 billion kroner, beating expectations of 5.58 billion kroner. Loan losses narrowed to 845 million kroner from 1.42 billion kroner against expectations for 1.04 billion kroner.

HD Danske Bank sees improved results
WC 172 words
PD 6 February 2014
SN RTE.ie
SC RTEI
LA English
CY Copyright 2014. RTE

LP 

Denmark's Danske Bank is set to issue its first dividend since the financial crisis began.

The move is a sign the bank is recovering from the financial crisis after lagging its Nordic peers due to burst property bubbles in Denmark and Ireland.

TD 

"Our financial results improved, but they were still unsatisfactory," Danske's chief executive Thomas Borgen said in the bank's full-year report.

"We still have a way to go to realise the full potential of Danske Bank, but we are confident that we are moving in the right direction," he added.

The proposed dividend of two crowns per share, the first since its pay-out for 2007, is higher than the 1.27 crown average forecast from analysts in a Reuters poll.

Meanwhile, Danske Bank today reported a profit before tax from core activities of 1.5 billion (11.5 billion crowns) for last year. The net profit was 51% higher than in 2012 and in line with the bank's revised guidance.

HD Denmark investigates Danske Bank over price manipulation
WC 139 words
PD 7 February 2014
ET 09:32
SN Reuters News
SC LBA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Reuters Limited

LP 

COPENHAGEN, Feb 7 (Reuters) - Denmark's public prosecutor for serious economic and international crime is investigating Danske Bank over price manipulation of a particularly serious nature, the bank said on Friday.

This has also been confirmed by the public prosecutor.

TD 

The bank said four employees from the banking operation and its mortgage lending unit Realkredit Danmark violated internal rules and may potentially have manipulated prices.

It said that it had found no evidence that other staff members were involved in the transactions. The four employees and their two superiors have been suspended, it said.

"We consider the matter to be very serious and are cooperating fully with the authorities," Chief Executive Thomas Borgen said in the announcement. (Reporting by Teis Jensen; Editing by David Goodman)

HD UPDATE 1-Denmark investigates Danske Bank over price manipulation
WC 259 words
PD 7 February 2014
ET 12:00
SN Reuters News
SC LBA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Reuters Limited

LP 

(Adds details)

COPENHAGEN, Feb 7 (Reuters) - Denmark's public prosecutor for serious economic and international crime is investigating Danske Bank over alleged price manipulation, the bank said on Friday.

TD 

In its statement Danske Bank said it was investigating four employees from the banking operation and Danske's Realkredit Danmark mortgage unit over alleged violation of internal rules and price manipulation.

When the bank found out it told the Danish Financial Supervisory Authority, which handed the case over to the public prosecutor, the bank said.

"We consider the matter to be very serious and are cooperating fully with the authorities," Chief Executive Thomas Borgen said in Friday's announcement.

The bank did not name the four Danske employees and their two superiors, who it said have been suspended. The bank said it had found no evidence that other staff were involved in the transactions being investigated.

One of the allegations covers transactions in February and March 2009 involving the mortgage bonds CIBOR Extra-CIBOR38.

The public prosecutor's office confirmed it had launched an inquiry, saying one of the transactions had changed the price of the bond to an artificial level.

Police later said the bank could face fines if the price manipulation allegations were found to be true. A Danske spokesman said the bank would not comment beyond its statement for now. ($1 = 5.4871 Danish crowns) (Reporting by Teis Jensen, additional reporting by Stine Jacobsen and Ole Mikkelsen; Editing by Jon Boyle)

HD Danske Bank accused of 'price manipulation'
BY By Richard Milne, Nordic Correspondent
WC 462 words
PD 7 February 2014
ET 12:02
SN Financial Times (FT.Com)
SC FTCMA
LA English
CY Copyright 2014 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.

LP 

Danske Bank has been accused of price manipulation "of a particularly serious nature" by Danish prosecutors, in the latest blow to the public image of the country's largest lender.

The accusations by the Danish public prosecutor for serious economic and international crime relate to corporate bond transactions in 2009 between Danske and Realkredit Danmark, Danske's wholly owned mortgage bank subsidiary.

TD 

"We consider the matter to be very serious and are co-operating fully with the authorities," said Thomas Borgen, Danske's chief executive.

The news comes just one day after Mr Borgen declared that the "financial and economic crisis is over and done with for Danske Bank" after it restored its dividend for the first time since 2007.

Danske has been plagued by problems after it felt the brunt of the bursting of the property bubbles in both Denmark and Ireland, where it had large operations.

A bungled marketing campaign that used images of Occupy Wall Street protesters, a public fight with Denmark's financial regulator, and the desertion of tens of thousands of customers raised eyebrows among customers and the Danish public.

Danske then ousted Eivind Kolding - its former chairman - as chief executive, claiming that it wanted "somebody with stronger qualifications within banking".

The accusations of price manipulation "under particularly aggravated circumstances" are directed against Danske, Realkredit and six Danske workers.

Danske said it discovered in an internal investigation that there might have been potential price manipulation during transactions in the corporate bond market between Realkredit and Danske in 2009 by four workers.

It added: "The internal investigation found no evidence that staff members other than the four in question were involved in the transactions. However, in view of the further investigation of the matter, the four employees and their two superiors have been suspended."

Two accusations were laid out. One is that, on February 13 2009, Danske and Realkredit entered into a DKr50,000 ($9,120) mortgage bond transaction "with a view to raising the day's average price as this was needed as a reference price for a customer transaction with Realkredit Danmark".

The accusation continues: "The transactions were suited to provide incorrect or misleading signals about the supply of, demand for or price on the security, and/or the transactions ensured that the price was at an unusual or artificial level."

The second is that, on March 6 2009, Danske and Realkredit agreed that Danske would change the "value date" on a DKr17.5m mortgage bond transaction at a price of 95.9. The accusation also states that they agreed Danske would not quote prices for the deal until Realkredit did a separate transaction for DKr650m of mortgage bonds at a price of 96.25.

HD Another low for banking sector with Danske's 'chaotic' exit
WC 261 words
PD 7 February 2014
SN Irish Independent
SC IINM
ED 3; National
PG 30
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Independent Newspapers Ireland Ltd

LP 

THE decision of Danske Bank to 'terminate' ''' thousands of customers accounts today further tarnishes the reputation of the banking sector in the eyes of consumers, if such a thing is possible. This is just one tranche of accounts that are to be closed over the coming weeks, as the Danish bank, which has just reported over 1bn in profits, withdraws entirely from the Irish banking market.

The bank confirmed yesterday that out of 15,000 current account holders 9,000 had yet to make alternative arrangements and it is these accounts which will be peremptorily closed today.

TD 

This may also effect some former customers trying to make other banking arrangements and who could now find themselves 'locked out' ''' of their accounts after the weekend.

The bank says it informed customers of 'timelines' ''' for the closure of accounts, but many of these letters were delivered in December. The sudden closure of accounts certainly seemed to come as a surprise to some customers, who maintain that the bank''''s withdrawal has been "chaotic and shambolic".

Danske Bank - the former National Irish Bank - said that the Central Bank had been kept "fully informed" of the closure process since the decision to leave Ireland was taken last October.

It certainly appears that the Central Bank should have insisted on Danske Bank making its exit in a much more high-profile manner that appears to be the case and should have ensured that it financed a public information campaign for its customers.

SE News; Front Page
HD Sticklers for deadlines, Danes just don't get Irish customers
BY Charlie Weston
WC 457 words
PD 7 February 2014
SN Irish Independent
SC IINM
ED 3; National
PG 13
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Independent Newspapers Ireland Ltd

LP 

THE handling by Danske Bank of the closure of its retail operations is very poor. The bank wrote to its thousands of customers in December telling them that the first batch of accounts would close at the end of this week. There was no follow-up press, radio or TV adverts to remind people of the impending deadlines. The letters notifying people of the closure of their accounts went out just before Christmas, a time when most families have too many other things going on to deal with the messy business of finding a new bank. You could be kind and put it all down to a clash of cultures. Executives in Danishowned Danske Bank set deadlines for terminating accounts and wrote to the customers. There is information on its website and telephone helplines. We did enough, they will have told themselves. That sort of approach may work in Denmark, but in Ireland we need reminders.

TD 

And as so many deadlines eventually end up being extended here, it is not unreasonable of Irish people to be surprised by Danske's rigid adherence to the closure dates it set for shutting savings, current accounts and credit card accounts. But further evidence of a badly arranged shutdown comes from the fact that Danske has also yet to tell any customers who were forced to open a current account with it to service a mortgage what new arrangements there will be. And it has yet to notify customers with shares in custody accounts of its plans on that front. There is also a reluctance on the part of the bank to put loans in place for those unable to clear credit card balances and overdrafts. Danske is shutting its personal banking operation here, but keeping its wholesale banking business. There is no reason it could not transfer credit card balances into personal loans. It is not the first bank to close its retail banking business in Ireland. Halifax/Bank of Scotland shut down a much bigger business in a far smoother fashion back in 2010. What has been lacking around the handling of the Danske Bank retail closure is some firm intervention from the Central Bank. Is it really acceptable in 2014 that people are to have no access to their money because their accounts have been frozen? The regulators should be demanding a much more pro-active approach from Danske. And it is to be hoped that there will not be similar horror stories emerging from the decision of ACC to shut its operations here and hand back its banking licence. The Central Bank needs to demand higher standards from the banks it regulates.

HD Bank locks 10,000 customers out of their accounts
BY Charlie Weston
WC 716 words
PD 7 February 2014
SN Irish Independent
SC IINM
ED 3; National
PG 1,13
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Independent Newspapers Ireland Ltd

LP 

Just 72 hours to withdraw funds from cash machines Danske Bank locks customers out of their accounts

THOUSANDS of customers of Danske Bank are set to be denied access to their money after the bank said it was closing their current accounts from today. The bank has confirmed that 15,000 current accounts are to be "terminated" and the majority of customers who hold these accounts have yet to shut them down and one.

TD 

Up to 10,000 people could find their funds frozen as they have failed to set up a new account with another bank. Danske said in October that it was closing its retail operations here.

Large numbers of those who have already started the switching process are also set to be locked out of their accounts before the new accounts can be set up.

A spokeswoman for the bank said: "Yes, some will be locked out of their accounts."

The bank said it was closing the current accounts today but it later conceded that it would allow these customers to use their debit/ATM cards over the weekend.

But by Monday, the accounts will no longer operate.

Customers who contacted the Irish Independent claimed the whole shut-down of Danske's retail operations was being handled in a "chaotic and shambolic" fashion.

Permanent TSB, to which large numbers are switching, is so worried about it that it is making arrangements to hand out 500 to each customer who has already signed up to switch from Danske but have chosen a date later this month for the tranfer to take effect.

Executives at Permanent TSB fear customers moving from Danske will have their funds and accounts frozen before the switches take place.

Under Central Bank rules, consumers are supposed to be able to agree a date for the transfer of accounts with their old and new banks and not to have it imposed upon them.

But banking sources accused Danske of imposing the shut-down for the first tranche of current accounts too hastily, even though many customers had nominated different dates for the transfer.

Continued on Page 13 Continued from Page One Irate customers said Danske was not answering phones, with others claiming the shut-down of its retail operations was being badly handled.

Customers complained that the letters they received about the closure deadlines arrived in December and the Christmas period, making it difficult to put new banking arrangements in place.

And they accused the bank of not doing any TV, radio or newspaper advertising to remind people of the various closedown deadlines.

Another customer claimed that Danske had initially given a longer period for customers to shut their accounts and find new banks when it first announced its intention to close its personal banking operation here last October.

Terminations Danske, whose parent company in Denmark yesterday reported profits before tax from core activities of 1.5bn for last year, defended its handling of the shut-down.

It said it had written to customers in tranches, setting out when accounts would be closed.

"The first tranche of letters issued in early December to customers with only a single product with Danske, ie a current account, a savings account or a credit card," a spokeswoman said.

She said customers with current accounts and savings accounts were given two months' notice of the closure of their account, with a deadline of February 7 set for the first tranche of terminations.

Another set of customers has until Friday, February 21, to put alternative banking arrangements in place. Customers with credit cards have until March 7. The spokeswoman added: "Where a customer has not yet taken action, their accounts will be terminated on February 7 in accordance with the terms of the account."

The bank confirmed that it had 15,000 current account customers, but 9,000 people had yet to close their accounts.

"We encourage customers to note the timelines referred to in their individual letters to ensure that they have sufficient time to effect their preferred option of closing or transferring their accounts to alternative institution," the bank said.

The Central Bank said Danske had given the notice to customers that it was required to provide.

HD Danske Bank Accused of 'Serious' Price Manipulation; Denmark's Largest Bank is Accused by Prosecutor for Bond-Trading Activities in 2009
BY Gustav Sandstrom
WC 431 words
PD 7 February 2014
ET 07:30
SN The Wall Street Journal Online
SC WSJO
ED WSJ.com
LA English
CY Copyright 2014 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved.

LP 

STOCKHOLMDanske Bank A/S, Denmark's largest bank by market value, said Friday it faces allegations from prosecutors of price manipulation "of a particularly serious nature" in connection with mortgage bond trading in 2009. Six employees have been suspended, the bank said.

The accusations, coming after Danske turned over to banking authorities evidence of irregularities that it uncovered internally, stem from corporate bond transactions between the bank and Danish peer Realkredit Danmark. After uncovering the activities, the bank informed the Finanstilsynet, the Danish financial regulator, which in turn handed the matter over to prosecutors.

TD 

"We consider the matter to be very serious and are cooperating fully with the authorities," Danske Chief Executive Thomas Borgen said in a written statement. Prosecutors have also brought charges against Realkredit Danmark and the six suspended Danske employees, who were unnamed.

Realkredit Danmark officials couldn't be reached for comment.

Danske Bank said it is being held liable for a transaction with Realkredit Danmark on Feb. 13, 2009 in "CIBOR Extra-CIBOR38 mortgage bonds". According to the accusations, that deal was aimed at raising the day's average price as this was needed as a reference price for a customer transaction with Realkredit Danmark worth around 12 million Danish kroner ($2.2 million).

Danske Bank said it is also being held liable for an agreement with Realkredit Danmark on March 6 the same year to change the value date of already agreed customer transactions so that they wouldn't affect general price information.

The allegations come after Denmark in 2012 announced a wide-ranging revamp and new oversight of the Copenhagen interbank offered rate, or Cibor, following heavy criticism of the country's reference interest rate in the wake of the U.K. Libor manipulation scandal. Regulators at the time feared the Cibor ratewhich guided the interest rates on a long list of Danish credit productswasn't accurate and lacked accountability. The regulators at the time said they would introduce new interest rates to supplement the Cibor and have the Danish FSA supervise the benchmark rate.

Danske Bank wasn't immediately available Friday to comment further on the matter.

On Thursday, the Danish lender reported stronger fourth quarter earnings and proposed paying its first dividend in five years. Mr. Borgen took the helm at Danske in September and quickly went to work trimming costs through head count reductions and other measures. He is also winding down some unprofitable ventures.

7 Feb 2014 10:00 EDT Danske Bank Accused of 'Serious' Price Manipulation

By Gustav Sandstrom

Danske Bank A/S, Denmark's largest bank in terms of market cap, said Friday that Danish prosecutors have accused it of price manipulation "of a particularly serious nature" relating to bond-trading activities in 2009, and six employees have been suspended in the matter.

The accusations are brought by Denmark's Public Prosecutor for Serious Economic and International Crime, the bank said in a news release. "We consider the matter to be very serious and are cooperating fully with the authorities," Danske Chief Executive Thomas Borgen said in a written statement.

Danske Bank in an internal investigation found that its own rules had been violated in connection with bond transactions between the bank and Danish peer Realkredit Danmark in the corporate bond market in 2009. The bank informed the Finanstilsynet, the Danish FSA, which in turn handed the matter over to prosecutors. Prosecutors are bringing charges against Danske Bank, Realkredit Danmark and six employees, it added.

Four staff members involved in the transactions have been suspended, together with their two superiors, Danske Bank said.

Danske Bank has confirmed that it is closing about 8,000 customer accounts this weekend.

But the bank said this only impacts customers who hold a standalone account, such as a current account or a savings account. Customers with more than one account will not be affected.

TD

Danske said that its phone lines are extremely busy today after media reports about what will happen their accounts over the weekend.

HD Banks open up today to win Danske customers
BY Charlie Weston
WC 517 words
PD 8 February 2014
SN Irish Independent
SC IINM
ED 3; National
PG 6
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Independent Newspapers Ireland Ltd

LP 

BANKSare taking the unprecedented step of opening their branches today in a bid to entice thousands of customers of Danske Bank who are having their accounts shut down. Danske Bank has confirmed that it is closing about 8,000 customer accounts this weekend after the account holders missed a deadline to close them and transfer any funds to other banks.

The Danish-owned bank is closing its retail operations here in phases, with the first wave of 15,000 people with only a single current account or savings account having their accounts closed.

TD 

The bank does not operate branches and customers yesterday reported having to wait up to 30 minutes to get through to telephone helplines.

And some customers said they were unable to move money out of Danske because its online operations had been removed for personal customers. However, this was denied by the bank.

Now AIB, Bank of Ireland and KBC Bank said they would open branches and keep phone lines open in a bid to get departing Danske customers to switch their accounts to them.

Branches AIB will open 30 branches around the country until 2pm every Saturday until March 8, when most Danske accounts will have closed.

Bank of Ireland said it would open 60 of its branches until 8pm every Thursday this month, and open eight locations on Saturdays.

KBC said hubs in Dublin, Cork, Limerick and Galway will open tomorrow from 10am to 2pm for Danske customers.

And Permanent TSB said it would open accounts for those affected from Monday and will make 500 available to those "locked-out" of their accounts.

Danske Bank yesterday defended its handling of the shutdown, but admitted that it was getting a huge volume of phone calls.

The bank said that for accounts that close this weekend, if a debit or ATM card exists on the account it will remain operational until Monday.

"Beyond this weekend, customers can withdraw their funds by contacting the bank who will issue a bank draft or facilitate the transfer of funds to another bank," it said.

Danske said that customers with multiple products have until February 21 to close or switch their accounts. Customers with credit cards have until March 21 to move to another credit card provider.

But financial adviser Michael Dowling was among those complaining that the shutdown process was poorly handled.

He is helping a 79-year-old pensioner who has been sent a 15-page letter from the bank telling her to "terminate" her credit card account.

If the woman, who is on a state contributory pension, does not pay off the balance she will have it converted into a two-year loan at an interest rate of 11.5pc, Mr Dowling of Abacus Finance in Clontarf, Dublin, said.

"The bank sends a confusing letter, gives no warning and does not offer to negotiate, that is not good enough," he said.

Danske said its phone lines will operate from 9am to 4.30pm over the weekend. Customers can contact the bank on 1890-866866.

SE COMPANIES - ROUND-UP
HD Prosecutors accuse Danske of 'serious' price fixing; BANKS
BY By Richard Milne, Nordic Correspondent
WC 243 words
PD 8 February 2014
SN Financial Times
SC FTFTA
ED London Ed1
PG 17
LA English
CY Copyright 2014 The Financial Times Ltd. All rights reserved. Please do not cut and paste FT articles and redistribute by email or post to the web.

LP 

Danske Bank has been accused of price manipulation "of a particularly serious nature" by Danish prosecutors, in the latest blow to the public image of the country's largest lender.

The accusations by the Danish public prosecutor for serious economic and international crime relate to corporate bond transactions in 2009 between Danske and Realkredit Danmark, Danske's wholly-owned mortgage bank subsidiary. "We consider the matter to be very serious and are co-operating fully with the authorities," said Thomas Borgen, Danske chief executive.

TD 

The news comes a day after Mr Borgen declared that the "financial and economic crisis is over and done with for Danske Bank" after it restored its dividend for the first time since 2007.

Danske has felt the brunt of the bursting of the property bubbles in both Denmark and Ireland, where it had large operations.

A bungled marketing campaign that used images of Occupy Wall Street protesters, a public fight with Denmark's financial regulator, and the desertion of tens of thousands of customers raised eyebrows among customers and the Danish public.

The accusations of price manipulation "under particularly aggravated circumstances" are directed against Danske, Realkredit and six Danske workers.

Danske said it discovered in an internal investigation that there might have been potential price manipulation during transactions in the corporate bond market between Realkredit and Danske in 2009 by four workers.

HD INSTANT VIEW 4-Norwegian inflation surge may bring quicker rate hike
WC 645 words
PD 10 February 2014
ET 04:40
SN Reuters News
SC LBA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Reuters Limited

TD 

(Adds Danske Bank, expands Swedbank quotes)
    OSLO, Feb 10 (Reuters) - Norway's core consumer inflation
rose by 2.4 percent in January, well above forecasts for 2.0
percent, raising the chance the central bank would bring forward
its next interest rate hike. 
    The crown currency firmed around 1 percent on the data.
    
 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
 NORWAY CONSUMER PRICES (pct)  Jan 2014    Dec 2013    Jan 2013
 Core CPI year/year               2.4         2.0          1.2 
 Core CPI month/month            -0.1        -0.1         -0.5 
 Headline CPI year/year           2.3         2.0          1.3 
 Headline CPI month/month         0.0        -0.1         -0.2 
 Index (base 1998)              135.1       135.1        132.1 
 ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

    Economists gave the following comments:
    
    --FRANK JULLUM, CHIEF ECONOMIST, DANSKE BANK
    "Prices were higher than expected."
    "Import price rose more than expected. The drop in prices in
January was smallar than normal, probably because of the weaker
crown in second half of 2013."
    "The CPI figures are volatile after Statistics Norway
changed how they calculate the figures, but the trend is up."
    "And we know the crown has continued to weaken in 2014, so
we expect the trend with higher import prices will continue for
some months."
    "Inflation is higher than Norges Bank's predictions. So the
market moves away from the probability of a rate cut."
    "We have GDP on Wednesday. If growth comes in at 0.4 to 0.5
percent as expected from the central bank, then we have a basis
for an adjustment up of the rate path."
    
    --KYRRE AAMDAL, SENIOR ECONOMIST, DNB MARKETS
    "Inflation was surprisingly high. So far it seems like it's
the import prices that contribute to increasing inflation as a
result of the weaker crown we saw last year."
    "Norges Bank is probably surprised by the impact after
inflation that tended to be slightly lower than expected for the
two previous months."
    "It's the effect of a weaker crown that temporarily
contributes to higher inflation but not in a longer term. This
probably has limited impact on the rate path and Norges Bank
probably wants to see more numbers before it shifts the rate
path upwards. In the market we see rates rising and the crown is
strengthening." 
    
    --JAN ANDREASSEN, CHIEF ECONOMIST, EIKA
    "January is the most important month for consumer prices, as
it sets the tone for the rest of the year, and this year the
numbers are surprisingly high."
    "Now we have a difficult combination of high inflation and
low or no economic growth."
    "Norges Bank should cut rates considering the low activity
and housing prices, but has for a long time wanted to prioritise
the fight against high credit growth. These numbers give them an
excuse to continue to postpone the rate cut that the economy
needs."
    
    --HARALD MAGNUS ANDREASSEN, CHIEF ECONOMIST, SWEDBANK FIRST
    "The price of imported goods was higher than I assumed. It
was due to higher prices on clothing and furniture, all of them
imported. It was also a bit higher due to (more expensive) food,
which seems to be imported foods. This is why we had a deviation
on the upside.
    "This will have no impact at all on interest rates because
it is broadly in line with Norges Bank's (forecast for
inflation) .. Even more so because it is not due to domestic
factors."
    
    --ERIK BRUCE, CHIEF ANALYST, NORDEA MARKETS
    "The inflation was stronger than expected and stronger than 
expectations from Norges Bank. On this basis rates should move
up."
    "If we look at the details, I suspect that the price
reductions in the January sales season were lower than normal,
and that prices then will rise by less (than normal) when the
sale is over. So it's too early to conclude."
    

 (Reporting by Oslo Newsroom)

HD Green REIT poised to buy five properties for 23m; Investment trusts deal with Danske Bank involves landmark city centre locations
BY Fiona Reddan
WC 415 words
PD 11 February 2014
SN The Irish Times
SC IRTI
PG 2
LA English
CY (c) 2014, The Irish Times.

LP 

Green REIT, the Irish-listed Real Estate Investment Trust, is set to buy five Dublin city centre properties in an off-market transaction with Danske Bank for 23 million. The deal is expected to close "imminently".

The transaction will leave the fund with 86 million of equity available for investment, which, together with the ability to raise up to 161 million of debt finance, will see the group look to capitalise on a more active market in 2014.

TD 

According to the fund's interim results, released yesterday, it has raised310 million in capital and invested some 214 million of equity to date.

In 2013, it invested 191 million at an initial yield of 9 per cent and, since then, the further 23 million has been contracted.

This 23 million investment consists of five properties with a total rent roll of 1.4 million, along with significant redevelopment potential. The "D2" portfolio comprises five properties in two locations, Molesworth Street and Ormond Quay.

Four of the five properties are located at 30-33 Molesworth Street, Dublin 2, in the city centre and are occupied by seven tenants paying "relatively low rents".

The fifth property is the Ormond Building, adjacent to the Four Courts. Over 50 per cent of the rental income comes from Dublin City Council, with 11 years to run on the lease. The remainder of the income is dominated by barristers' chambers.

The fund's net asset value stood at 299.7million, or 96.7 cent per share, at the end of 2013. It reported a passing rent of 17.3 million last year.

Gary Kennedy, chairman of Green REIT, says the company still has the financial capacity to take advantage of further attractive investment opportunities. "The effective deployment of further capital will grow the size of our portfolio, enhance our income stream and drive shareholder returns."

Central Park development

The property investment company, established last July, was the first REIT to establish in Ireland, following the introduction of REIT legislation, and it is listed on the Irish Stock Exchange.

Earlier this month, the fund was selected as the preferred bidder, along with US real estate giant Kennedy Wilson, to buy the Central Park development in Leopardstown, south Dublin, for 310 million.

In late 2013, Green REIT acquired a property on Mount Street, Dublin 2, for 6.35 million.

SE Markets
HD Danske CEO Says Price-Rigging Allegations Hurt Work to Boost Brand; CEO Calls Traders' Alleged Scheme 'Unacceptable' Breach of Internal Practices
BY Gustav Sandstrom
WC 732 words
PD 11 February 2014
ET 10:54
SN The Wall Street Journal Online
SC WSJO
ED WSJ.com
LA English
CY Copyright 2014 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved.

LP 

COPENHAGENThomas Borgen, chief executive of Denmark's Danske Bank AS, said allegations of bond-price manipulation have dealt a blow to efforts to rebuild a brand damaged following a state bailout during the 2008 financial crisis.

In an interview at the bank's Copenhagen headquarters Tuesday, Mr. Borgen called the allegations "unacceptable" and a "setback." The country's biggest bank by market capitalization disclosed on Feb. 7 that Danish prosecutors were investigating potential bond-price manipulation by a small group of traders in 2009.

TD 

The irregularities surfaced in an internal investigation by the lender, which referred the matter to the authorities. Prosecutors are investigating Danske and its subsidiary Realkredit Danmark, in addition to individual employees.

"We have four employees who have breached internal rules and regulations," Mr. Borgen said. "Further police investigation must establish whether there was manipulation."

The bank has been working to streamline operations following years of poor profitability. Slow economic growth and heavy loan losses in Ireland damaged its bottom line.

Mr. Borgen, six months into leading Danske Bank, has already trimmed costs through headcount reductions and other measures, and is winding down unprofitable ventures. The bank last week reported stronger fourth-quarter earnings and proposed its first dividend in five years.

But Mr. Borgen is eager to make the Danske Bank brand a more trusted name. The lender's image had been tarnished among some customers because of the belt-tightening measures and a recent advertising campaign alluding to "Occupy Wall Street" imagery.

"We have come a long way to rebuild the brand, but there is a long way left to go," Mr. Borgen said.

"We have to work our way through it."

If the Danske Bank traders are convicted, they could face a maximum sentence of four years in prison, deputy state prosecutor Hans Fogtdal said Tuesday.

"We will now interrogate a number of people, but do not know when a decision can be expected" on whether further action should be taken, Mr. Fogtdal said. "Danske Bank has said it will fully cooperate, which makes things easier."

No charges have been filed.

The state is alleging that Danske Bank and its Realkredit Danmark unit in 2009 engaged in a price-rigging scheme that overcharged customers when traders sold mortgage bonds at artificially high prices. In total, the traders manipulated prices for more than 650 million Danish kroner ($119 million) in mortgage bonds, according to Mr. Fogtdal.

Mr. Borgen declined to say why the alleged incidents were reported almost five years after they occurred.

"It's a case which we have identified as possible breach of procedures," Mr. Borgen said. "It was important to us to report it as soon as possible,"

Realkredit Danmark declined to comment separately on the matter.

At this point, it is unknown how much customers actually lost in the transactions. Lars Krull, a researcher with Denmark's Aalborg University, estimated there may have been an overcharge of around 2.3 million kroner for the customers.

"It's only 0.35% or so, but 2.3 million kroner is still a lot of money, and all manipulation is too much manipulation," he said.

Anders Thomsen, a 30-year-old teacher in Copenhagen, said the Danske Bank situation leaves a bad taste in his mouth. "I find this totally unacceptable....Danske Bank got a loan from the state during the financial crisis."

The recent price-rigging allegations come at a time when Prime Minister Helle Thorning-Schmidt has been working to ease concerns about the unrelated sale of ownership in a state-run energy company to Goldman Sachs Group Inc. That deal was criticized for giving unfair preference to the U.S. investment bank.

The alleged price-rigging scam is being viewed by Danske Bank as an isolated incident. "We have no indications that there should be any other incidents than what we have reported to the Danish FSA," Mr. Borgen said.

But it is still a sign that there could be a problem in the wider Danish bond market, said Niels Mengel, chairman of the Danish Shareholders' Association.

"We think this is a very serious problem," Mr. Mengel said. "For private investors, it's critical that we get the right price for bonds, otherwise you cannot trust the system."

The trial opened yesterday of a financial adviser charged with money laundering over 600,000 allegedly part of proceeds of a Northern Bank raid when 26.5 million was stolen in Belfast 10 years ago. Timothy Cunningham (65), Woodbine Lodge, Farran, Co Cork, has denied nine counts of money laundering at Cork Circuit Criminal Court.

TD

Tom O'Connell SC , prosecuting, said the State would produce evidence that Mr Cunningham had "dispersed money in an unconventional or unorthodox way".

HD 'We switched lender after half a century'
BY CHARLIE WESTON
WC 236 words
PD 17 February 2014
SN Irish Independent
SC IINM
ED 3; National
PG 19
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Independent Newspapers Ireland Ltd

LP 

EAMONN and Paula Kelly (pictured left) reckon they had been with the same bank for around 50 years. But in the past few months they have taken the plunge and switched their current accounts.

The couple each had accounts with Danske Bank before they met and when they married they set up a joint account. Back then it was called National Irish Bank.

TD 

But Danske is shutting down its retail operations, which prompted the couple to make the move to Permanent TSB.

The couple are in their 70s and live in Rooskey in Co Roscommon.

Mr Kelly says they were being charged around 18 every quarter and found it more difficult to bank with Danske, as a while ago it shut all the branches near them - in Athlone, Strokestown and Carrick-on-Shannon.

Because of their age, they now get free banking from Permanent TSB.

Mr Kelly worked with the ESB but is retired. Asked if he was nervous about switching banks after being so long with the same institution, he said: "We were not nervous about it. We knew we just needed to do it. And the switching process could not be easier."

He said that both Danske and Permanent TSB facilitated the switch and did the administrative work for them. And there is a Permanent TSB branch down the road in Longford.

CHARLIE WESTON

SE News
HD Man admits laundering 250,000 bank raid cash
BY Georgina O'Halloran
WC 254 words
PD 19 February 2014
SN Irish Independent
SC IINM
ED 3; National
PG 24
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Independent Newspapers Ireland Ltd

LP 

A FINANCIAL adviser has pleaded guilty to laundering more than 250,000 of the proceeds of a Northern Bank robbery 10 years ago.

Timothy "Ted" Cunningham (65) of Farran, Co Cork, admitted two counts of money-laundering arising out of the 26.5m Northern Bank robbery at Cork Circuit Criminal Court.

TD 

The first offence occurred on or about January 15, 2005, at Tullamore, Co Offaly, and involved the transfer of 100,040 in sterling by Cunningham to John Douglas.

The second offence took place on or about February 7, 2005, at Ballincollig, Co Cork, and involved the transfer by Cunningham of 175,360 in sterling to John Sheehan and obtaining three cheques to a total value of 200,000.

The charges state that Cunningham was reckless as to whether the money represented the proceeds of criminal conduct, namely a robbery at the Northern Bank Cash Centre, Donegall Square West, Belfast, on December 20, 2004.

Cunningham had gone on trial last Thursday charged with nine counts of money laundering.

He had denied all charges, which involved sums totally approximately 600,000.

The financial adviser was yesterday re-arraigned on two of the charges, before a jury of seven men and five women, to which he pleaded guilty.

Counsel for the State Tom O'Connell (SC) said that was acceptable to the State.

Judge Sean O Donnabhain discharged the jury. He remanded Cunningham on bail and adjourned the matter for sentencing to February 27.

HD Danske Bank to sell Denmark's first Additional Tier 1 bond
BY By Aimee Donnellan
WC 117 words
PD 26 February 2014
ET 10:35
SN Reuters News
SC LBA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Reuters Limited

LP 

LONDON, Feb 26 (IFR) - Danske Bank is preparing to sell Denmark's first Additional Tier 1 bond and has hired Bank of AmericaMerrill Lynch, BNP Paribas, Danske Bank, Goldman Sachs, HSBC and JP Morgan to act as lead managers.

The Danish lender will meet with investors starting Monday March 3rd to discuss the euro-denominated bond, which will be perpetual but callable after six years. The loss-absorbing offering will temporarily write-down if the bank's Common Equity Tier 1 ratio falls below 7%.

TD 

(Reporting by Aimee Donnellan; editing by Alex Chambers, Julian Baker)

HD *Fitch Rates Danske Bank's Additional Tier 1 Capital Instruments 'BB+(EXP)'
WC 646 words
PD 27 February 2014
ET 11:16
SN Dow Jones Institutional News
SC DJDN
LA English
CY Copyright 2014, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

LP 

27 Feb 2014 11:16 EDT Press Release: Fitch Rates Danske Bank's Additional Tier 1 Capital Instruments 'BB+(EXP)'

 
 
The following is a press release from Fitch Ratings:

TD 

Fitch Ratings-London-27 February 2014: Fitch Ratings has assigned Danske Bank's (A/Stable/F1) planned issue of Additional Tier 1 capital notes an expected rating of 'BB+(EXP)'.

The final rating is contingent upon final documents conforming to information already received.

KEY RATING DRIVERS

- The notes will be CRD IV compliant perpetual non-cumulative resettable Additional Tier 1 instruments (with a call after six years). The notes are subject to partial or full temporary write-down if the Common Equity Tier 1 (CET1) ratio of Danske Bank falls below 7%, and any coupon payments may be cancelled at the discretion of the bank.

The expected rating is five notches below Danske Bank's Viability Rating (VR) in accordance with Fitch's criteria for assessing and rating bank subordinated and hybrid securities. The notching reflects the notes higher expected loss severity relative to senior unsecured creditors (two notches) and higher non-performance risk (three notches) given the fully discretionary coupon payments. Fitch believes Danske Bank's capital buffer being above the 7% CET1 trigger and the minimal capital ratio taking into account the additional buffer on Danish systemically important financial institutions is sufficient to limit the notching for non-performance risk to three (which could otherwise result in wider notching).

Given the securities are perpetual, their deep subordination, coupon flexibility and going concern mandatory write-down of the instruments, Fitch has assigned 100% equity credit.

RATING SENSITIVITIES

- As the notes are notched from Danske Bank's VR, their rating is primarily sensitive to any change in this rating. The notes' rating is also sensitive to a wider notching if Fitch changed its assessment of the probability of the notes' non-performance risk relative to the risk captured in Danske Bank's VR.

SE News
HD Financier sentenced in Northern Bank case
BY Ralph Riegel
WC 318 words
PD 28 February 2014
SN Irish Independent
SC IINM
ED 3; National
PG 16
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Independent Newspapers Ireland Ltd

LP 

A FINANCIER who laundered some of the proceeds of the 26.5m Northern Bank robbery received a five-year suspended sentence and was ordered to quit the finance industry.

Timothy 'Ted' Cunningham (65) avoided jail as the Circuit Criminal Court heard he was "used" by a ruthless and vicious IRA gang with the aim of "mingling" cash from the December 2004 raid with money from legitimate business deals.

TD 

Cunningham was sentenced after he pleaded guilty to two counts of money laundering on the second week of his Cork Circuit Criminal Court trial.

The robbery - on December 20 2004 - remains the biggest bank raid in Irish history with a total of 26.5m being stolen (32m). The father of three was originally convicted and sentenced to 10 years in prison in April 2009 for money laundering following a 10-week trial. But that conviction was later quashed on the basis of a problem with the specific type of warrant used by gardai.

A retrial was ordered which opened before Judge Sean O Donnabhain on February 13.

In the trial''s second week, Cunningham pleaded guilty to two of the nine charges.

Subversive Inspector Colm Noonan said the Gardai and PSNI are convinced the Northern Bank robbery was committed by a ruthless IRA gang.

A number of people with suspected subversive contacts were placed under surveillance and, as a result of intelligence obtained, Cunningham, of Woodbine Lodge, Farran, Co Cork, came to Garda attention.

Inspector Noonan said gardai accept that Cunningham had no subversive involvement but was "used" by the gang to help launder some of the money.

After his 2009 conviction, Cunningham served three years and two months in prison.

Judge O Donnabhain said that in light of Cunningham''s age, his health, his guilty plea and his willingness to resign from his firm, he would impose a suspended term.

SE Ireland
HD Financier avoids jail for money laundering; Suspended sentence for man caught with Northern Bank robbery cash
BY Barry Roche
WC 597 words
PD 28 February 2014
SN The Irish Times
SC IRTI
PG 6
LA English
CY (c) 2014, The Irish Times.

LP 

A 65-year-old financial advis

er has been given a five-year suspended sentence for his part in the money laundering of about 275,000 of the 26.5 million stolen in the Northern Bank robbery in Belfast almost 10 years ago.

TD 

Ted Cunningham of Woodbine Lodge, Farran, Co Cork, was sentenced at Cork Circuit Criminal Court yesterday after pleading guilty last week to two counts of money laundering four days into his trial on nine counts of money laundering.

Cunningham pleaded guilty to money laundering 100,040 on January 15th, 2005, by transferring it to John Douglas in Tullamore, Co Offaly, and in doing so being reckless to it being the proceeds of the Northern Bank robbery.

He also pleaded guilty to money laundering 175,360 on February 7th, 2005, by transferring it to John Sheehan in Ballincollig, Co Cork, and receiving three cheques totalling 200,000.

Yesterday, Insp Colm Noonan outlined the background to the case when an armed IRA gang held up the Northern Bank Cash Centre at Donegall Square West in Belfast on December 20th, 2004, in what was the biggest bank robbery to date on the island.

"It was an extremely sophisticated operation involving the use of firearms, a large number of personnel over a 24-hour period and it is the view of those investigating the robbery that it was carried out by the IRA," said Insp Noonan.

Criminal subversives

Garda in Cork noticed sterling cash moving in the area prior to the robbery, but after the raid they examined these movements and the activities of criminal subversives in Cork which led to the arrest of three men with 94,000 at Heuston Station in Dublin in February 2005. This in turn led them to Cunningham who may not have been aware of the identity of those who carried out the Northern Bank raid but displayed a recklessness with regard to the origin of the money that he gave to unsuspecting business people, said Insp Noonan.

Financial director

At the time, Cunningham had his own company, Chesterton Finance, in Ballincollig, Co Cork, and Cunningham had recently rejoined the company as a financial director, said Insp Noonan.

Cross-examined by defence counsel Hugh Hartnett SC, Insp Noonan said garda accepted Cunningham had no involvement in subversive activity but had been utilised by criminal subversives because of his financial experience and business contacts.

The court heard Cunningham had been convicted of 10 counts of money laundering in 2009 arising out the same investigation, but relating to a much larger sum. He was sentenced to 10 years, but was released after three on appealing his conviction.

Mr Hartnett asked that the court not impose a custodial sentence given Cunningham's age, poor health, and the fact that he had already served three years prior to his appeal, plus his guilty plea to the two offences.

Judge Sen Donnnabhin paid tribute to the professionalism of the Garda investigation and he noted Cunningham's guilty plea, which he said was a clear acknowledgement of his part in money laundering.

"It puts his involvement beyond all doubt and all from out of his own mouth. There are no appeals, there is no doubt anymore."

Mr Hartnett said Cunningham would give up his role as financial director of Chesterton Finance, and Judge Donnabhin welcomed that as he imposed a five-year sentence suspended on condition he have no involvement in any financial company for five years.

HD *S&P Rts Danske Bank Proposed Additional Tier 1 Cap Notes 'BB+'
WC 1588 words
PD 3 March 2014
ET 03:26
SN Dow Jones Institutional News
SC DJDN
LA English
CY Copyright 2014, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

LP 

3 Mar 2014 03:26 EDT Press Release: S&P Rts Danske Bank Proposed Additional Tier 1 Cap Notes 'BB+'

TD 

 
 
The following is a press release from Standard & Poor's: 
 
STOCKHOLM (Standard & Poor's) March 3, 2014--Standard & Poor's Ratings 
Services said today that it had assigned its 'BB+' long-term issue rating to 
the proposed perpetual additional Tier 1 capital notes to be issued by Danske 
Bank A/S (A-/Stable/A-2). The rating is subject to our review of the notes' 
final documentation. 
 
This will be the first issue by Danske Bank A/S, or by any Nordic bank, of an 
additional Tier 1 security (AT1), which we understand will be compliant with 
the European Commission's Capital Requirements Directive (CRD IV), which 
implements Basel III in the EU. We understand that the notes will rank senior 
to ordinary shareholders, absent a trigger event, and subordinate to any 
senior creditors, including Tier 2 creditors of Danske Bank A/S. 
 
In accordance with our criteria for hybrid capital instruments, the 'BB+' 
rating reflects our analysis of the proposed instruments, and our assessment 
of Danske Bank A/S' stand-alone credit profile (SACP) at 'bbb+' (see "Bank 
Hybrid Capital Methodology And Assumptions," published Nov. 1, 2011, on 
RatingsDirect). 
 
The 'BB+' issue rating stands three notches below the bank's SACP, 
incorporating: 
     -- The deduction of two notches, which is the minimum downward notching 
from the SACP under our criteria for bank hybrid capital instruments; and 
     -- Our consideration that the notes have a going-concern loss-absorption 
feature in the form of nonpayment of coupons at the issuer's discretion, 
resulting in an additional notch. 
 
We expect the evolution of the regulatory ratio specified in the notes over 
each of the reporting dates over the next 18-24 months will not likely drop 
from the current level of 14.7%, which should provide a buffer of more than 
401 basis points over the trigger level. Consequently, we do not deduct any 
further notches with reference to the high trigger mandatory write-down 
feature. It would be activated if Danske Bank A/S' estimated consolidated 
common equity Tier 1 ratio under CRD IV is less than 7.0% on any quarterly 
financial period end date or extraordinary calculation date. 
 
We could cap the ratings on the proposed instrument at 'BB' or lower if we 
believe that the distance from the trigger of a mandatory suspension of 
coupons would not exceed 300 basis points, in the case of Danske Bank A/S with 
its SACP of 'bbb+'. Although the full details are subject to change, we 
understand that the Danish authorities, as part of the capital conservation 
plan, may limit Danske Bank A/S' making payments on Tier 1 instruments, paying 
out bonuses, and distributing dividends, should the bank's capital ratio fall 
below a certain level. However, we expect that Danske Bank A/S, with a total 
capital ratio of 21.4% at year-end 2013, will remain in the range of 301-400 
basis points or more above the level of such potential mandatory suspension of 
coupons in the next 18-24 months. 
 
We will assign "intermediate" equity content to the notes when they get formal 
regulatory approval for inclusion into regulatory Tier 1 capital. The 
instruments meet the conditions for "intermediate" equity content under our 
criteria because: 
     -- They are perpetual; 
     -- They do not contain a step-up clause; and 
     -- They have loss-absorption features on a going-concern basis, given the 
bank's flexibility to suspend the coupon at any time. 
 
RELATED CRITERIA AND RESEARCH 
     -- Banks: Rating Methodology and Assumptions, Nov. 9, 2011 
     -- Bank Hybrid Capital Methodology And Assumptions, Nov. 1, 2011 
 
Complete ratings information is available to subscribers of RatingsDirect at 
www.globalcreditportal.com[http://www.globalcreditportal.com] and at spcapitaliq.com. All ratings affected by 
this rating action can be found on Standard & Poor's public Web site at 
www.standardandpoors.com[http://www.standardandpoors.com]. Use the Ratings search box located in the left 
column.  Alternatively, call one of the following Standard & Poor's numbers: 
Client Support Europe (44) 20-7176-7176; London Press Office (44) 
20-7176-3605; Paris (33) 1-4420-6708; Frankfurt (49) 69-33-999-225; Stockholm 
(46) 8-440-5914; or Moscow 7 (495) 783-4009. 
 
Primary Credit Analyst: Alexander Ekbom, Stockholm (46) 8-440-5911; 
                        alexander.ekbom@standardandpoors.com 
Secondary Contact: Sean Cotten, Stockholm (46) 8-440-5928; 
                   sean.cotten@standardandpoors.com 
Additional Contact: Financial Institutions Ratings Europe; 
                    FIG_Europe@standardandpoors.com

HD BRIEF-Change in Danske Bank's executive board
WC 87 words
PD 4 March 2014
ET 08:11
SN Reuters News
SC LBA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Reuters Limited

LP 

COPENHAGEN, March 4 (Reuters) - Denmark's largest bank Danske Bank said on Tuesday: * Robert Endersby, who has been Head of Group Risk Management and a member of the Executive Board at Danske Bank since 2012, has announced that he will resign from his position at the end of 2014, at the latest.

* The Bank is starting a process to search for Robert Endersby's successor.

TD 

Further company coverage: (Reporting by Teis Jensen)

HD Danske Bank to price inaugural AT1 with 5.75% coupon
BY By Helene Durand
WC 160 words
PD 5 March 2014
ET 04:21
SN Reuters News
SC LBA
LA English
CY (c) 2014 Reuters Limited

LP 

LONDON, March 5 (IFR) - Danske Bank is set to price its inaugural Additional Tier 1 issue with a 5.75% coupon on the back of overwhelming interest for the trade.

The Danish lender began marketing the issue, which is expected to be rated BB+/BB+ by S&P/Fitch, at 6% area on Wednesday morning, but this has now been revised tighter.

TD 

The order book is now closed and the expected EUR750m perpetual non-call April 2020 issue will be priced later today.

Bank of AmericaMerrill Lynch, BNP Paribas, Danske Bank, Goldman Sachs, HSBC and JP Morgan are leading the issue, which will be temporarily written down if the issuer's and/or the group's Common Equity Tier 1 ratio falls below 7% on a transitional basis. (Reporting by Helene Durand, editing by Julian Baker)

7 Mar 2014 08:28 EDT Danske Bank Names Jim Ditmore Group COO

TD 

    By Dominic Chopping

Danske Bank A/S (DANSKE.KO) said Friday that it has appointed Jim Ditmore as Group chief operating officer and member of the Executive Board with effect from Apr. 21, 2014. 

 
   MAIN FACTS:

-Mr. Ditmore, is a 53 year-old American who is currently Chief Technology Officer, Senior Vice President, at Allstate Insurance, Chicago, Illinois.

-At Danske Bank, Mr. Ditmore will be in charge of Group IT and Group Services.

-At 1326 GMT shares traded 0.3% higher at DKK147.30.

SE Finance
HD Swiss private equity targets rural assets for $300m fund EXCLUSIVE
BY SUE NEALES, RURAL REPORTER
WC 742 words
PD 21 March 2014
SN The Australian
SC AUSTLN
ED 1 - All-round Country
PG 17
LA English
CY  2014 News Limited. All rights reserved.

LP 

ONE of Europe's largest private equity and managed fund investors is in Australia scoping major acquisitions for its new $US300 million ($332m) specialist agricultural vehicle, the Harvested Resources Fund.

Swiss firm Adveq Real Assets, which currently has $US5.4 billion of assets under management worldwide, has already made a major rural purchase in Australia through HRF, as part of a consortium that bought 18,000ha of almond orchards on the Murray River near Robinvale last month for $211m from Olam International.

TD 

Adveq Asia-Pacific head David Seex said yesterday its Harvested Resources Fund had contributed $37m, or 11 per cent of the purchase price of the Australian almond deal, with two major international pension funds, US-based Municipal Employees' Retirement System of Michigan and the $US57bn Danish Danica Pension Fund contributing the other $110m of equity.

Now the still-open Harvested Resources Fund is looking to make nine other big farming acquisitions worldwide, each averaging about $US30m, within the next three years.

Mr Seex said all of the nine potential purchases had been identified, with ``more than

one'' being Australian rural assets.

The Adveq chief said that Australian farms were particularly attractive to form the asset base of the HRF, which had already attracted $US136m in funds, because the land tenure system was secure, land is still relatively cheap,

Continued on Page 18

Continued from Page 17

infrastructure standards were high and crops were produced in what were off-seasons to the northern hemisphere.

A bonus is Australia's proximity to the emerging mega-market of China, which last week was forecast by the Economist Intelligence Unit to buy an astounding 59 per cent of all Australia food and rural exports by 2030.

He also rejected suggestions from other corporate investors that had bought Australian farming interests and say it is impossible to make an adequate return on capital investment in Australian agriculture because of the vagaries of the weather.

Adveq locked in an advantageous 9 per cent rental yield on the purchase, indexed for uncapped inflation, when it bought the three million Victorian almond trees from Olam in February -- and immediately leased them back to Olam, which is now fully owned by the Singapore government fund Temasek Holdings.

``Australia is also an environment where there is high visibility in what we can expect; each transaction tends to be specific about the asset and the crop,'' Mr Seex told The Australian yesterday.

``What we are looking for are agricultural products that are highly (linked) to the fundamental food story. This is about the crops and animal products the land produces, not a real estate (speculative) play.''

Mr Seex said other agricultural fields identified by Adveq where Australia had a comparative advantage included beef and dairy farming, as well as nuts and olives.

But there are few such farming ventures big enough to have the $20-$30m price tag that Adveq is looking for. However, Mr Seex did concede the Harvested Resources Fund has been scoping dairy opportunities in Tasmania, where Australia's largest dairying venture, the Van Diemen's Land company in northwest Tasmania, is for sale.

Other rural opportunities around the world being investigated by Adveq for inclusion in the HRF, which will close off to investors in May this year, include sorghum, grains and other nut crops.

``But it's not just about the crops we like, but the deal on offer,'' Mr Seex said. ``If the price is attractive, the commodity is right, the returns sustainable and it fits our diversification model we will invest. For example, the almond orchards were a good price at below replacement cost because Olam wanted to restructure its balance sheet.''

Mr Seex said a key factor in HRF's investment focus was to invest in crops and farming systems that required minimal costly inputs such as electricity, fuel, irrigation water and labour, effectively ruling out many horticultural and intensive farming operations such as hothouse crops, piggeries and intensive poultry farms.

Farms and raw food production are also the top priority assets being targeted, with downstream food manufacturing or processing assets unattractive, because of the unpredictable nature of future input costs such as energy.

Mr Seex believed Australia was well-served by top quality, well-educated farm managers and rural asset managers who can look after local agricultural investments for large global private equity players such as Adveq.

SE News
HD Lobbyist received 40,000 from Kelly [CORRECTED]
BY John Mooney
WC 629 words
PD 23 March 2014
SN The Sunday Times
SC ST
ED 1; Eire
PG 6
LA English
CY  2014 Times Newspapers Ltd. All rights reserved

CX 

Publisher Notice: THIS ARTICLE IS SUBJECT OF A LEGAL COMPLAINT FROM ANGELA KERINS

LP 

MICHAEL PARKER, a lobbyist and PR adviser who works for Rehab, received two personal payments totalling 40,000 from John Kelly, the property developer who claims he had a strategy to acquire Roslyn Park, the charity's complex in Sandymount.

Parker received the money in September 2006 via two cheques written from Kelly's personal account at Allied Irish Banks. The cheques were made out to the lobbyist by name, and dated September 8 and 15 respectively. They were lodged into an account held at the National Irish Bank, according to records obtained by The Sunday Times.

TD 

Kelly has outlined payments he made to Parker in a letter to the Dail's Public Accounts Committee in which he also outlined dealings with Angela Kerins, the Rehab chief executive. The committee is investigating corporategovernance issues at the charity, which receives 80m in public funds annually.

In the statement, Kelly alleged Parker asked him to make the payments to him personally, and that they were part of his plan to purchase Roslyn Park. "I wish to inform the committee that Mr Parker specifically requested of me that in relation to this discreet and delicate work with Rehab, that I should not pay his usual costs through his company Insight Consultants Limited in the normal course, but that I should pay Mr Parker directly," Kelly's statement said.

"I did so from my own bank account and made cheques out to Mr Parker personally for sums in the order of 40,000."

Kelly separately retained the services of Parker's PR firm, which is based in Sandyford, to advise on development projects.

The developer has already claimed he spent large amounts of money on hospitality for Parker and Kerins in the hope of being allowed to acquire Roslyn Park for development at the height of the property boom. He says he spent approximately 100,000 hiring private jets to take the two on excursions to London, and permitting Kerins to use his twin-engine Agusta to travel.

The developer, who now lives in Britain, is due to meet gardai in the coming weeks to assist with their investigation. In a statement issued through solicitor Robert Dore, Parker said any payments he received from Kelly were lawful and treated in a lawful manner.

"My client has never denied he received payments from John Kelly. For the avoidance of any doubt, no payment received from John Kelly was in any way connected with his supposed effort to acquire Rehab Headquarters," Dore's statement said. It does not clarify why the payments were made out to Parker personally, or what they were for.

Parker has given conflicting accounts of his relationship with the former developer whose story is, in part, corroborated by independent witnesses. The lobbyist initially said he did some PR work for Kelly and had once travelled with him and Kerins by helicopter as a "birthday treat", but said he never went to London with the two, or acted as an intermediary. He has denied any knowledge of Kelly's plan to purchase Roslyn Park.

Parker later confirmed he had travelled to London on business with Kelly, but did not recall if Kerins was present.

He initially denied owning any property company with Kelly but later admitted he was a co-director with Kelly of Kelpach Optima Properties, which was dissolved in 2012. The lobbyist owned 20% of Optima, according to the Companies Registration Office. Parker also owned shares in Shamrock &Rose Investments, a London-based property firm of which Kelly was a director and shareholder.KELLY SPENT 100,000 HIRING PRIVATE JETS TO TAKE THE TWO ON EXCURSIONS

I did so from my own bank account and made cheques out to Mr Parker personally for sums in the order of 40,000.

Kelly separately retained the services of Parkers PR firm, which is based in Sandyford, to advise on development projects.

The developer has already claimed he spent large amounts of money on hospitality for Parker and Kerins in the hope of being allowed to acquire Roslyn Park for development at the height of the property boom. He says he spent approximately 100,000 hiring private jets to take the two on excursions to London, and permitting Kerins to use his twin-engine Agusta to travel.

The developer, who now lives in Britain, is due to meet gardai in the coming weeks to assist with their investigation. In a statement issued through solicitor Robert Dore, Parker said any payments he received from Kelly were lawful and treated in a lawful manner.

My client has never denied he received payments from John Kelly. For the avoidance of any doubt, no payment received from John Kelly was in any way connected with his supposed effort to acquire Rehab Headquarters, Dores statement said. It does not clarify why the payments were made out to Parker personally, or what they were for.

Parker has given conflicting accounts of his relationship with the former developer whose story is, in part, corroborated by independent witnesses. The lobbyist initially said he did some PR work for Kelly and had once travelled with him and Kerins by helicopter as a birthday treat, but said he never went to London with the two, or acted as an intermediary. He has denied any knowledge of Kellys plan to purchase Roslyn Park.

Parker later confirmed he had travelled to London on business with Kelly, but did not recall if Kerins was present.

He initially denied owning any property company with Kelly but later admitted he was a co-director with Kelly of Kelpach Optima Properties, which was dissolved in 2012. The lobbyist owned 20% of Optima, according to the Companies Registration Office. Parker also owned shares in Shamrock & Rose Investments, a London-based property firm of which Kelly was a director and shareholder.
